{
  "answer": "In *Andreas*, the sea becomes a perilous adversary during Andrew's voyage to rescue Matthew, churning violently in a divinely ordained storm that tests the faith and resolve of Andrew and his companions. The waves threaten to overwhelm the ship, filling the thanes with terror as \"the deep was disturbed, the whale-mere was stirred,\" winds howl, sails soak, and sea-monsters loom, yet Andrew remains steadfast, praying amid the chaos.[^1] Here the sea functions primarily as a trial, testing the saint's unyielding trust in God (and indirectly his followers') against mortal fear of death.\n\nIn *Elene*, by contrast, the sea serves more as a vast barrier and conveyor of news, separating Constantine from his mother Elene's triumphant discovery of the True Cross in Jerusalem. Messengers must cross \"the high sea\" and \"swan-road\" (a conventional kenning for ocean) to relay the glad tidings—\"how the men with the victory-queen had made a safe journey over the swan-road\"—and return with further commands, while Elene sends the nails-forged bridle \"over the ocean’s stream.\"[^2] The sea here separates the emperor from immediate \"rescue\" or involvement in the sacred quest, emphasizing distance rather than direct peril to the protagonists.\n\nWhat do you make of these contrasting roles for the sea—active antagonist in *Andreas* versus distant divider in *Elene*?\n\n[^1]: Cynewulf, *Andreas*, [paragraphs](/works/cynewulf-andreas-07b573/01/translation/#p-8fd929).\n\n[^2]: Cynewulf, *Elene*, [paragraph](/works/cynewulf-elene-d2d132/01/translation/#p-f5d1f1).",
